          <span purpose="section-marker">PART 6</span>
          <h1>Preparing for the Future of Device Management</h1>
          <p>Do organizations have full insight into the state of their devices? Or are they underprepared to manage security and compliance in an increasingly remote world? As we found, many organizations are prepared, with near-full enrollment of their devices in an MDM solution that provides effective visibility, incident response, and security across devices. However, many other organizations are challenged in their approach to device management, starting with confusing and unsupported deployment.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="subsection">
          <h2>Takeaways</h2>
          <p>If you’re looking to strengthen your MDM solution, or simply looking for better ways of thinking about device management, here are a few actionable tips and takeaways.</p>
          <div purpose="report-list">
            <h3 purpose="report-list-header">Protect remote workers with zero trust, TLS, and 2FA</h3>
            <p>With workforces split almost evenly between fully remote, half remote, and no remote employees, focus on designing solutions using tools that are as effective in an office as they are when people are on an unknown internet connection. Not assigning trust to the network location of your devices is the safer approach, even if you don’t have anybody remote right now. Plus, not assigning trust is a useful business continuity mechanism if anything prevents employees from working at the office. To keep devices safe in the office as well as in remote locations, move away from VPNs to granular proxies with TLS and two-factor authentication (2FA) which don’t allow for lateral movement.</p>
            <h3 purpose="report-list-header">Either manage for Linux or don’t use Linux</h3>
            <p>Respondents above said that the second most frequent platform used in their organization but that’s not currently managed is Linux. The best approach is to either use Linux, or don’t. If you have many Linux workstations stuck in that gray area of being necessary yet not fully managed, see what would be needed to get your Linux workstations up to spec when it comes to secure configuration and monitoring. Otherwise, it’ll become more of a burden and vulnerability point than benefit.</p>
            <h3 purpose="report-list-header">Start managing containers now</h3>
            <p>Identify your container security needs. Many respondents are not sure if containers are in use at their company, and others do not currently use them. In both cases, there likely will be a need to secure containers soon, and organizations who don’t yet use them still have time to create their container strategy. Start by evaluating your existing IT and security stack and see what gaps you have in terms of vulnerability discovery and real-time monitoring of container workloads.</p>
            <h3 purpose="report-list-header">Make Windows part of your MDM</h3>
            <p>Move Windows workstations from legacy GPO management to MDM and Autopilot. Because there were other options to manage them, Windows systems are less often managed by MDM, and MDM policies are still catching up. However, in a remote world we can’t assume laptops will ever be connected to the LAN to receive their policies. Like container security above, now’s the time to bring Windows — the number one platform most use yet not managed above — into your MDM solution.</p>
            <h3 purpose="report-list-header">Use open APIs for real-time compliance</h3>
            <p>Many of the challenges above centered around being able to verify compliance in real time, and have visibility across all devices in the organization. In order to make compliance simpler, use tools with open APIs that let you query the status of devices, but that also alert you when a policy check fails on a device. This way, remediation can happen immediately.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
